                "href": "/profile/Helen-Lindsey-2"
            },
            "answer_text": "The Open University, established in the UK in 1969, was the world\u2019s first open university. It\u2019s the biggest university in the UK, it is ranked among the top 500 universities worldwide, and its degrees are highly respected by employers. However, there are now numerous \u2018open universities\u2019 worldwide. They share the same ethos of making higher education more accessible by having minimal entry requirements and many of them also use distance learning, either exclusively or together with in-person tutorials or lectures. And any university degree is \u2018valid\u2019 as long as it has the proper accreditation. Wikipedia has a list of the world\u2019s open universities here: List of open universities - Wikipedia with links to short articles about them. The best place to find out more about the courses, qualifications and accreditation is on the university\u2019s own website. You should be able to contact the university\u2019s student support team for advice about choosing the right study programme. You may also be able to find out what the current students and alumni think about the university and the course you\u2019re interested in. More importantly, you should find out what employers think. Depending on your choice of career, you may discover you don\u2019t need a degree. Alongside technical competence and experience many companies look for employees with the right \u2018soft\u2019 skills\u2014such as creativity, problem solving, team work and communication skills\u2014rather than a specific degree. So any course that helps you gain the skills you need will be worthwhile. ",
