            "author_info": {
                "name": "John Orchard",
                "href": "/profile/John-Orchard-8"
            },
            "answer_text": "In the same way as any British university an OU degree course is written and validated by external assessors, academics expert in their field and who usually hold senior positions in other institutions. The standards having been set, the external assessor is responsible for ensuring that assessment and outcomes meet the rigour and standards expected for an academic qualification in good standing and comparable to any other of equal standing. Because of the scale of the OU student population compared to others, it will differ in that those presenting the course locally will not be the authors of much of the course materials. The teaching materials from the OU for undergraduate courses is world renowned and used as an exemplar for other institutions. Those universities in the UK who appear in the top 100 in the world rankings of universities are happy to utilise the OU for their own academics carrying out additional degrees and continuing professional development. All of the above, to my mind, guarantees the validity of an OU degree ",
